  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Costa Rica: Local Recycling Knowledge Transfer in San Juan, Ciudad Quesada</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The objective of this project is to foster social cohesion and integration for migrant populations through local knowledge sharing and economic empowerment related to recycling in the San Juan neighborhood of Quesada City (Costa Rica). Prevailing poverty, unemployment, an absence of law enforcement, widespread violence and crime, and the regular arrival of migrants to the area, have caused this neighborhood to near a potential crisis situation. This has been exacerbated by the COVID-19 pandemic, as it has created a socioeconomic downturn which is adversely affecting all of Costa Rican society, and a burden that is falling heaviest on migrants. The foundation of this project is based on initiatives already underway in San Juan to empower women in the community as drivers of economic and social development. IOM aims to expand the impact of the San Juan Recycling Center, a cooperative formed by Nicaraguan women, by introducing value added processes and encouraging the transfer of recycling knowledge.</narrative>
  </description>
